<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="representative specimen">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Representative Specimen.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">New Zealand (North Island)</emphasis>
: North Auckland, Cliffs north of the Manukau heads, December 1870, T. F. Cheeseman s.n., (AK 4473).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Distribution of Lepidium aegrum, Lepidium amissum, Lepidium castellanum (Kermadec Islands only), Lepidium banksii, and Lepidium crassum." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10753" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Endemic. New Zealand, North Island, where it was recorded from 'between Manukau Heads and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Karekare’">Karekare'</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B11" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1906. Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1906">Cheeseman 1906</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B12" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1925. Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2 nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1925">1925</bibRefCitation>
), not 
<pageBreakToken pageId="22" pageNumber="23" start="start">the</pageBreakToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘Titirangi’">'Titirangi'</normalizedToken>
noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirk, T" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" refId="B60" refString="Kirk, T, 1899. The Student's Flora of New Zealand. Government Printer, Wellington." title="The Student's Flora of New Zealand. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1899">Kirk (1899)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was last collected from the west Auckland coastline in 1917 and is presumed to be extinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="recognition">
<paragraph pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Recognition.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had previously been included in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirk, Trans. et Proc. New Zealand Inst. 24, 423" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium obtusatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, perhaps because the species have no obvious floral differences and both have deeply notched and winged silicles with tapering bases. However, from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirk, Trans. et Proc. New Zealand Inst. 24, 423" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium obtusatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the non-rhizomatous, suberect growth habit; arching, sparingly leafy stems (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Holotype of Lepidium amissum de Lange et Heenan." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10754" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
); long persistent, deeply, and sharply incised rosette and lower stem leaves (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Basal stem leaves of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10755" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figs 17</figureCitation>
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Basal stem leaf of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10756" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">, 18</figureCitation>
); upper stem leaves which are lanceolate, narrowly oblanceolate, to narrowly obdeltoid and mostly prominently toothed, with up to 6 pairs of deeply incised teeth, and with a truncate apex bearing 3-4 prominent teeth. The inflorescences of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are larger, only sparsely leafy when mature, and without associated vegetative stems (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Upper-stem leaves and inflorescences of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10757" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). The silicles are smaller than those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirk, Trans. et Proc. New Zealand Inst. 24, 423" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium obtusatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Mature silicle of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10758" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<pageBreakToken pageId="23" pageNumber="24" start="start">Ecology</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Little is known about the habitat preferences and ecology of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, beyond that it grew on sea cliffs (
<bibRefCitation author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B11" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1906. Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1906">Cheeseman 1906</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B12" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1925. Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2 nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1925">1925</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
